\subsection{The phloem}
\subsubsection{Structure and function}
The phloem is a tissue that allows long-distance transport (translocation) of photosynthates, i. e. the product of photosynthesis. Redistribution of water and other compounds is another one of its functions. Photosynthates must be transported from their source, typically mature leaves, to areas of growth that are unable to produce enough assimilates, such as young leaves, fruits, or roots. Storage organs, including roots, tubers and rhizomes, can be both sink, when accumulating nutrients, and source, when providing said nutrients to the plant body during winter or other stress-inducing times (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). Seeds do the same, transitioning from source to sink when they germinate and need to consume the resources that they accumulated as starch to support the new plant’s growth (Rascio et al., 2017).
\smallskip

In Angiosperms, which are the main object of research on the phloem, xylem and phloem form vascular tissues that extend throughout the plant body, with the xylem being usually closer to the centre of the stem (or the root), and the phloem on the outer side (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). The two continuously exchange water. %specify primary vs secondary growth? 
\smallskip

The phloem is made up of living cells belonging to three different categories: sieve elements, companion cells and parenchymatic cells. In Angiosperms, sieve elements are roughly cylinder-shaped cells that are stacked on top of each other, forming a sieve tube (Rascio et al., 2017). Cross walls separating the cells are perforated by pores (Figure \ref{fig:sieve}), forming sieve plates, to achieve symplastic continuity and a higher hydraulic conductance inside the tube (Peters \& Knoblauch, 2022). As sieve cells do not possess a nucleus, a cytoskeleton and other essential organelles, each sieve cell is associated with one or more companion cells. Plasmodesmata provide a close symplastic relationship between sieve cells and companion cells. The latter have intense metabolic activity and are responsible for the survival of the sieve cells. They also contribute to the transport of photosynthates from mesophyll cells in leaves, where they are produced, to sieve cells (Rascio et al., 2017).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth, angle=0]{images/sieve.png}
    \caption{\textit{Hypocotyl of Cucurbita maxima. Electron micrograph of a longitudinal section of two sieve tube elements. The pores of the sieve plate are visible between the two elements. The inset shows sieve plate pores. Image taken from Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002}}
    \label{fig:sieve}
\end{figure}

Phloem sap is rich in sucrose, varying from 0.3 to 0.9 M in concentration. In addition to sucrose, the phloem of certain plant families also contains high concentrations of sugar alcohols like mannitol and carbohydrates like raffinose and stachyose. Other solutes in lower concentrations include amino acids, hormones, proteins and inorganic solutes (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). 
\smallskip

Long-distance transport in the phloem is usually explained by the pressure-flow hypothesis, formulated by Ernst Münch in the 1920s. The hypothesis states that mass flow of water and solutes in the phloem is driven by an osmotically induced pressure gradient between source and sink organs (Figure \ref{fig:munch}). The loading of photosynthates into the sieve elements at the source causes a low osmotic potential ($\Psi_s$), which in turn causes a negative water potential ($\Psi_w$), so that water is drawn into the phloem from neighboring xylem tissue \textbf{and thus increase the turgor pressure near the source}. The opposite phenomenon happens in the sink organs, where photoassimilates are unloaded from the sieve elements and water potential becomes more positive, leading water to leave the phloem as well and the turgor pressure to decrease. This difference in turgor pressure ($\Delta P$), which is higher at the source and lower at the sink, pushes the fluid along the phloem from source to sink (Knoblauch et al, 2016). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth, angle=0]{images/Munch_schema_tagl.png}
    \caption{\textit{Relationship between xylem and phloem. Water enters the phloem at the source and leaves at the sink because of a water potential difference ($\Delta\Psi_w$), while source-to-sink mass flow is made possible by a difference in turgor pressure ($\Delta P$). Image taken from Rascio N. et al., 2017.}}
    \label{fig:munch}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Source-sink interrelationship}
Doing experiments on the phloem can be difficult, which is why it has been called “the least understood plant tissue”. Usually, experiments have to be done on whole plants, as you cannot detach source tissues from sink tissues without stopping the sap flow.  % rich tissue in resources, it will be attacked by predators/ parasites, etc. so: protection mechanisms are very strong; plant isolates the sensor you put in (seal off sensor).1 species Ricinus does not do that. Slightly toxic. For most plants you need indirect methods (labeling or measuring what comes out - proxy). Few methods that are expensive. Also, it is soft, difficult to take samples. 
Even the Münch hypothesis needs further testing, especially on the issue of sieve tubes conductance being high enough to allow pressure flow (Knoblauch et al, 2016). % not that relevant, maybe
\smallskip

Another area of interest is source-sink interrelationship, which is particularly useful for a deeper understanding of carbon allocation, defined as the regulation of the distribution of carbon among various pathways (accumulation, transport, metabolism). Starch is the main molecule that plants use for accumulation, functioning as an energy and carbon reserve, as opposed to as sucrose, which is mostly used for transport (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). It has been known for a long time that plants are able to adjust their starch and sucrose production according to different conditions. For example, if all but one leaf of soybean are shaded for 8 days, the source leaf experiences an increase in the rate of net photosynthesis, a decrease in starch concentration and an increase in sucrose concentration (Thorne \& Koller, 1974). % this last part is not essential
\smallskip

% acclimation to changing source–sink relationships
Carbon allocation is influenced by communication between source and sink, namely a decreased sink demand can lead to a decrease in the speed of phloem transport and to limitations in source organ activity (Taiz \& Zeiger, 2002). This ensures better coordination among source photosynthetic activity, phloem translocation and sink organ demand. 
\smallskip

Decreased sink demand can happen, for example, if a plant undergoes defruiting, or if its roots are cooled. In the first case, sink size (the total biomass of sink tissue) is reduced, in the second case sink activity (rate of uptake of photosynthates)  is limited. %find info on temperature and growth
Sink size and sink activity co-regulate sink strength, the ability of the sink organ to import photoassimilates (Balasubramanian et al., 2023).
\smallskip 

Communication between source and sink can happen through various means, including transport sugars themselves. According to this model, decreased sink demand causes high sucrose levels in the phloem, which in turn cause down-regulation of phloem loading at the source. Thus, carbohydrates accumulate in the source (mesophyll cells), which can lead to downregulation of photosynthesis (Chiou \& Bush, 1998). Generally speaking, low sugar levels cause higher photosynthetic activity, reserve mobilization and transport towards sink organs, whereas high sugar concentration encourages growth and storage, as summarized by Figure (\ref{fig:sugar}) (Rolland et al., 2002).   


\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/Source-sink.png}
    \caption{Effects of sugar on source-sink activity. Image taken from Rolland et al., 2002.}
    \label{fig:sugar}
\end{figure}


% Source-sink relationship can be explored by applying a variety of treatments, such as girdling and defruiting, to plants, and can have applications in agriculture as well, if fruits are the sink organs being studied (probably cut this).
Several studies have been performed over the years about the relationship between sink demand and photosynthetic activity. For example, in Frank et. al, 2006, the authors girdled \textit{Coffea arabica} branches at their base, that is to say they removed a ring of phloem to create a closed system environment. They subsequently measured total soluble sugar concentration ($SSC_m$) and maximal leaf net $CO_2$ assimilation rate $A_{max}$ on the mature leaves of the girdled branches. The results showed that $A_{max}$ was negatively correlated to $SSC_m$, that it was higher in branches with higher fruit loads and that it decreased during the day. A conclusion was drawn that there was sink feedback down-regulating photosynthesis \textit{e.g.} low fruit loads demanded less photosynthates, therefore photosynthetic activity decreased. It is thought that the feedback is mediated by the accumulation of sugars in the leaf phloem, which inhibits phloem loading. 
\smallskip

A similar experiment (Da Matta et al., 2007) on coffee involved 4 different treatments: 
\begin{itemize}
\item complete defruiting and maintenance of the full leaf area
\item half crop load and full leaf area
\item full crop load and full leaf area
\item full crop load and half leaf area. 
\end{itemize}
The first treatment resulted in the lowest net photosynthetic rate (\textit{A}) and stomatal conductance (\textit{g}), the third treatment had the highest \textit{A} and \textit{g}, while the other two treatments had intermediate results. However, here a different conclusion is proposed: the decreased \textit{A} in the first treatment is thought to be caused not by direct sink feedback, but by the lower stomatal conductance, as (\textit{A}) and (\textit{g}) were correlated. The reason for the lower \textit{g} remains unknown.
% maybe add another paper or two with similar experiment (with peach and/or apple trees)

From a genetic perspective, carbon accumulation in leaves has been connected to changes in transcription of genes that encode photosystems I and II and to a general decreased expression of photosynthetic genes (Paul and Foyer, 2001). % this could be cut out

Other than fruits, roots can also be studied as sink organs down-regulating photosynthesis, as this thesis will investigate.
