\section{Aim of the thesis}
The present work was conducted in the framework of Xin Zhuang’s Doctorate research. The wider scope of the experiment was a study on the effects of sink limitation on \textit{Betula pendula} source activity and carbon translocation in the phloem (Zhuang et al., in progress). This thesis focuses on part of the results, namely the effects of sink limitation on canopy photosynthesis, the hypothesis being that decreased sink activity limits source photosynthetic activity.
\smallskip
% be clear about my results vs whole experiment
Sink activity reduction was achieved by cooling the soil around the roots of 12 saplings, while 8 other trees were left untreated to function as controls. Gas exchange variables, such as $CO_2$ net assimilation and photosynthetic efficiency, were measured with the purpose of researching how the sink limitation created by soil cooling affected leaf photosynthetic activity. 
\smallskip

I am also reporting on the results of the water status monitoring (water potential monitoring) during the experiment. Here, soil cooling is expected to cause stress for the saplings, with less root water uptake and a decrease in water potential and stomatal conductance. The stress and the lower water uptake could also contribute to a lower stomatal conductance and lower photosynthesis, which might not be exclusively a result of direct feedback from the sink (decreased sink demand). 
% is this right? we limit sink activity + side effect: hydraulic conductivity between root and soil (water has nore trouble moving from soil to xylem) - water potential measures that (references).
