\subsubsection{Water potential}
%what is water potential, etc from textbook
% pressure chamber is explained in Rascio, as well 
The pressure chamber (Figure \ref{fig:pressure}) is a device for measuring water potential by applying pressure to a leaf thanks to a nitrogen tank. For our experiment, two leaves were taken from each tree and inserted in the chamber one at a time, with the cut end of the stem exposed outside of it. 
Pressure was then applied until water appeared at the surface of the exposed end. This is the amount of pressure that is equal and opposite to the water potential measurement. Therefore, higher values of pressure indicate higher stress for the tree. Maximum instrument operating pressure was 100 Bar \citep{PMS_Instrument_Company_2009}.
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/pressure_chamber.jpg}
    \caption{\textit{Pressure chamber in the greenhouse.}}
    \label{fig:pressure}
\end{figure}

%second image?
Measurements were taken in the early afternoon to make sure they were comparable, as water potential changes during the day, usually having the most negative values at midday. For each tree, two leaves were chosen to be measured and then an average was calculated and used for further analysis.
%$ \prescript{13}{}{\(CO_2\)} $

% add temperature instrument information

\subsubsection{Isotope pulse-labeling}
 For our experiment, the labeled ${}^{13} CO_2$ was pumped into plastic bags that had been wrapped around the birches' canopy. Labeled carbon  was then traced with Picarro's G2201-i Isotopic Analyzer, as it was transported from the source (leaves) to the sink organs, via the phloem. Chambers were sealed at two different locations along the stem and connected to the analyzer, so that the carbon could be traced when it respired. The difference in time lags between the appearance of labeled C at the first and second location can be used to establish phloem sap velocity \citep{Epron_D._et_al._2019}. However, this data is still being processed by Xin Zhuang, as it requires complex analysis, therefore it will not be discussed any further in this thesis.
%image?

\section{Statistical analysis}
For the statistical analysis, I used the programming language R.
\smallskip

The first part of the analysis tested whether there was a significant difference between the photosynthetic activity of cooled trees and control trees by analysing four variables: \textit{A}, \textit{E}, \textit{gsw} and \textit{$A/C_i$}. % is this correct English/ understandable?
The possibility of a significant difference among the four batches had to be taken into consideration as well, as they were measured during different parts of the growing season, starting from early June and ending in mid August. % is this right? 
\smallskip

Employing a parametric ANOVA was not possible, as the distribution of the data was not normal. Therefore, this data was tested for difference in significance ($P<0.05$) using the Scheirer–Ray–Hare test, which is a non-parametric test used for a two-way factorial design (Sokal and Rohlf, 1995).  
\smallskip

An example of the code used for the this part, for the variable \textit{A}, is given below:

\begin{verbatim}
    SRH_A <- scheirerRayHare(avg.A_2 ~ batch + treatment, 
             data=licor_avg_2)
\end{verbatim}

The second part of the analysis investigated the effect of soil cooling on those same 4 gas exchange variables, looking for a correlation between gas exchange variables and temperature values. The significance was once again set at $P<0.05$. % this sentence needs rephrasing
Because the distribution was not normal, linear regression was not suitable, so the gamma distribution model was used for \textit{A} and \textit{$A/C_i$}, whereas the General Additive Model (GAM) was employed for \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}. %short description of GAM?

Examples of the code are given below for \textit{A}:

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA <- glm(formula = licor_avg_2$avg.A_2 ~ licor_avg_2$batch +
    licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, family = Gamma(), data = licor_avg_2)
\end{verbatim}

And for \textit{E}:

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaE <- glm(formula = licor_avg_2$avg.E_2 ~ licor_avg_2$batch + 
    licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, family = Gamma(), data = licor_avg_2)
\end{verbatim}
    
The models were validated with the help of diagnostic plots (Zuur, 2009), as shown in Figure \ref{fig:diagnostics}, for \textit{A}.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/diagnostic_plot_A.png}
    \caption{\textit{Diagnostic plots for the gamma distribution model (A  soil temperature). The four plots show response residuals (observed minus fitted values), Pearson residuals, scaled Pearson residuals and deviance residuals.}}
    \label{fig:diagnostics}
\end{figure}

The data is not normal, so the plots are supposed to show a lack of pattern (Zuur, 2009). % i don't know whether to put the diagnostic plots here, because I don't understand the statistics very well (only the basics) e. g. the different residuals
\smallskip

The same models and validation were used to examine the effect of water potential on the 4 gas exchange variables, with the following code (for \textit{A}):

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA2 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A_2 ~ licor_avg_3$batch 
    + licor_avg_3$water_potential, data=licor_avg_3, family=Gamma())
\end{verbatim}


\cleardoublepage

\section{Results}
This section will discuss results pertaining to batch 1, 2 and 4, whereas batch 3 will not be included due to anomalies found throughout the data analysis. 
\smallskip

The first part of the analysis aimed at comparing the photosynthetic activity in control trees and treated trees. The four gas exchange variables all showed a significant difference, with 3 of them (\textit{A}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}) having a p-value of 0.00000. % rephrasing
The boxplots (Figure \ref{fig:A}, Figure \ref{fig:E} and Figure \ref{fig:gsw}) show that the control trees had significantly higher values than the treated trees. The difference between values of the two groups is represented with a boxplot. The box includes the values between the first and the third quartile and is divided by a line, the median. The "whiskers" show the values outside of the central 50\%. 
For instance, the median of \textit{A} values for the controls was about 9 $\mu mol m^{-2} s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 5 $\mu mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A.png}
    \caption{\textit{$CO_2$ assimilation rate in cooled and control trees. }}
    \label{fig:A}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{E} values for the controls is about $2x10^{-3}$ $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, while the median for the treated trees is about $5x10^-4$ $molm^{-2}s^{-1}$. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/E.png}
    \caption{\textit{Evapotranspiration rate in cooled and control trees.}}
    \label{fig:E}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{gsw} values for the controls was about 0.14 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 0.05 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/gsw.png}
    \caption{\textit{Stomatal conductance to water vapor in cooled and control trees.}}
    \label{fig:gsw}
\end{figure}

Photosynthetic efficiency was also significantly different in control trees and treated trees, however the p-value was higher (0.00689). This can be seen in boxplot \ref{fig:A-Ci}: control trees have higher values than treated trees, but the medians of the two groups are closer to one another (0.03 for the controls and about 0.2 for the treated trees). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A-Ci.png}
    \caption{\textit{Photosynthetic efficiency in cooled and control trees.}}
    \label{fig:A-Ci}
\end{figure}

The fourth variable $A/C_i$ is defined as photosynthetic efficiency, or the amount of carbon that is assimilated by the leaf normalized by the \(CO_2\) concentration inside the leaf.

